TERA — Logical Filtering and Measurement Loop

Overview

TERA defines a minimal logical filter for evaluating information under dynamic conditions.
Only observations that remain measurable, reproducible, and proportionally consistent are considered stable.
Unverified or non-measurable constructs remain in a deferred (WAIT) state.


---

Core Principle

Information is not accepted by definition, but by validation.

\text{Stability} = \text{measurable consistency over time}

A valid statement must satisfy:

observable reference

measurable relation

logical proportionality



---

Logical Filter

TERA applies a three-state evaluation:

ACCEPT → consistent with observation and measurement

WAIT → insufficient or incomplete information

REJECT → contradiction to observed reality


This filter prevents premature conclusions and enforces structural coherence.


---

Measurement Loop

The system evolves through a minimal loop:

\text{Observe} \rightarrow \text{Measure} \rightarrow \text{Compare} \rightarrow \text{Update}

Each iteration refines the informational state.


---

Constraint

A statement must remain plausible within three sentences.

If it cannot be:

explained

related

measured


it remains unvalidated.


---

Summary

TERA treats knowledge as a dynamic system stabilized through measurement, comparison, and iterative correction.


---

One-Line Definition

Knowledge is stable when it survives repeated observation, measurement, and logical filtering.


